Gbagbo, the first head of state to stand trial in The Hague, and his deputy Charles Blé Goudé, were both cleared of crimes against humanity in January, and released the following month.

Gbagbo faced charges of crimes against humanity over the 2010-2011 bloodshed following a disputed vote in the West African nation.

For more on this, Samora Mangesi spoke to Clemence Bectarte, Litigation Co-ordinator for the International Federation for Human Rights...

